make their communities attractive to outsiders. The result has been a standardized, interchangeable system of education not overly demanding for either students or teachers, one that involved parents and local voters in its governance and finance. Innovative in its focus on bottom-up processes generated by individual behaviors rather than top-down decisions by bureaucrats, Making the Grade provides a new perspective on education reform that emphasizes how public schools form the basis for the localized social capital in American towns and cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEducationxEconomic aspectsxUnited States. 0aEducationxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aEducational changexHistoryx20th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aEducational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool districtsxFinancexUnited States. 0aSchool districtsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aSchool districtszUnited StatesxFinance. 0aSchool districtszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226251318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226251318.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles